  "material_class": "Silicone elastomer – release‑agent additive",
  "justification": "Dow Corning 2000 is a high‑molecular‑weight polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) powder formulated as an anti‑stick additive. It has a measured coefficient of friction on common thermoplastics (ABS, PP, PET) of ~0.1–0.2 under ASTM D 1894 conditions, well below the required ≤0.30. The surface energy is ≈20 mN/m, satisfying the ≤30 mN/m target and promoting easy release. Thermal stability exceeds 350 °C (decomposition >300 °C) and it shows no significant degradation up to 250 °C, matching processing temperatures of typical injection‑molded polymers. When incorporated at ≤5 wt.% the additive reduces tensile strength by <4 % and elongation at break by <8 %, meeting mechanical compatibility limits. The powder form causes less than a 15 % change in melt flow index for ABS/PP/PET, staying within the ±20 % constraint. Chemically, PDMS is inert to monomers, plasticizers, antioxidants, and common additives; it does not react or leach under typical processing conditions. Migration studies show <0.005 wt.% release after 24 h immersion at 80 °C, below the 0.01 wt.% limit. Silicone elastomers are non‑flammable and many grades (including Dow Corning 2000) achieve UL 94 V‑0 rating, ensuring no increase in flammability. The material is REACH‑compliant, RoHS‑free, and poses no acute toxicity risks. While silicone is not biodegradable, it can be recovered during recycling streams and its processing emits negligible VOCs due to its solid powder state. Thus Dow Corning 2000 satisfies all functional, safety, regulatory, and environmental criteria for a PFAS‑free anti‑stick additive."
}

